article.headline: Lynx have won four straight at home
article.linkText: Smith's 22 points help Lynx calm Storm
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Katie Smith made the most of her minutes
Sunday night.

Smith, playing the entire game in foul trouble, scored 22 points
in just 19 minutes to lead the Minnesota Lynx to a 73-70 victory
over the Seattle Storm.

"It was rough," Smith said of sitting for most of the game.
"These types of games you have to keep your head in there.

"Obviously I knew my chance was going to come at some point,"
she said.

That chance came with 6:20 left in the game and Minnesota
trailing 54-51.

"I looked and her and asked if she was ready, and she said
'yeah!" coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "I just felt it was
time."

Playing with five fouls, Smith scored 15 of the last 20 points
for the Lynx. She also had the assist on a crucial 3-pointer by
Stacey Lovelace.

"Honestly it took me a couple minutes to get going," Smith
said.

"She was cold, but when she knocked down that first shot we
knew we'd be all right," point guard Kristi Harrower said.

Harrower had 13 points and seven rebounds and Nicole Ohlde added
12 points for the Lynx, who have won four straight at home and have
beaten the defending WNBA champions in both matchups this season.

Rookie Suzie Batkovic had 12 points and Simone Edwards added 11
for Seattle, which has lost three of four. Lauren Jackson had 13
rebounds, but was held to six points on 1-of-11 shooting.

Sue Bird finished with just eight points and gave everyone a
scare in the last minute of the game when she got hit in the face
with an elbow and fell to the floor. Bird has broken her nose twice
in the last two seasons and plays with a mask.

She stayed in the game and scored Seattle's last six points.

"It's fine," Bird said.

Smith picked up two quick fouls and got her fifth just under
four minutes into the second half.

With Smith resting, Seattle came back to tie the game at 47 with
9:30 left on Simone Edwards' turnaround jumper. The Storm took
their first lead two minutes later on Bird's first basket, a
fast-break layup that made it 52-51 with 7:29 left.

When Smith finally returned, she scored eight straight points
during one stretch to put Minnesota ahead 61-58 with four minutes
left.

With 1:18 left in the game, Smith penetrated and kicked the ball
out to Lovelace for a 3-pointer that gave Minnesota a 66-62 lead.
Smith's foul shot made it 67-62 and the Storm never had a chance to
tie it down the stretch.

Minnesota took an early 10-3 lead, scoring five points on free
throws, as both teams opened the game shooting poorly from the
field. The Lynx were 1-for-8 and the Storm 2-for-10 at the start.

The Lynx extended their lead to 26-15 at the 7:02 mark on
Vanessa Hayden's nifty post move in the lane. Seattle took a cue
from Minnesota, though, and fought back by getting to the foul
line. The Storm made 9 of 10 foul shots to close the half and get
within 34-29.
